 :tx/rationale "UAQ INSIGHT 14: TRANSFER IS RECONCILIATION, NOT WEIGHT COPYING. Cross-project merge is not ML transfer learning (opaque weight matrix → target domain). It is reconciliation of two knowledge bases through set union (C4), the same operation used for multi-agent coordination. When store A (braid, 36 sessions) merges with store B (Go CLI, 3 sessions): schema union is automatic (same binary, same layers). Policy weights resolve via LWW (A's calibrated weights win on recency). Hypothesis merge adds A's 36 data points to B's 9 — combined dataset of 45. The calibration function computes error over ALL 45. KEY INSIGHT: The system doesn't need boundary names to match. It needs to OBSERVE that predictions fail and adjust. When A's calibrated weights produce bad predictions on B's data, that's an axiological divergence (SEED.md §6 type 6). The reconciliation taxonomy detects and classifies it. The calibration loop adjusts. The merge of two stores IS an observation. The quality of the merge (did predictions improve?) IS data for meta-calibration. THE RECURSION: Merge is harvest at the inter-project level. Harvest takes agent experience → store datoms. Merge takes another store → datoms. Both are set union. Both produce potential conflicts. Both feed through reconciliation. It's the same operation at different scales — individual observation, session harvest, cross-project merge. SPEC: C4 (CRDT merge), ADR-FOUNDATION-019 (UAQ), ADR-FOUNDATION-014 (convergence thesis). VERIFICATION: After merge, per-boundary error should be measurably different (not necessarily lower — the merge might increase error for some boundaries while decreasing for others, indicating domain-specific calibration needs)."
